      • addAddlInfo

        public void addAddlInfo(java.lang.CharSequence param)
        Appends the specified AddlInfo to the end of the collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Input allowed for this field when one or more of the currencies is a user defined precious metal.This field is used to input additional information which corresponds to the tag 72 on MT601. Validation Rules: Mandatory when FX-OTC and one of the currency involved is metal i.e either trade or delivery currency, DELIVERY.DETAILS,METAL.TYPE and METAL.UNIT contains 'OTH'/'OTHR' and SWIFT message is to be processed. Input not allowed for other contract types.

        Parameters:
        param - the AddlInfo to append
        Returns:
        nothing

      • addSecBenAdd

        public void addSecBenAdd(java.lang.CharSequence param)
        Appends the specified SecBenAdd to the end of the collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: This field is used when the secondary counterparty (This is normally the broker)of the deal instructs us to pay funds to another party who does not have an account with us. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several instalments. If the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the beneficiary details should be entered in the BENEFICIARY.NO field. If unknown to us, details should be entered in this multi-value field. Note that, where the beneficiary requests the funds into an account he has with us, this should be specified in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. It is important to note that when the Beneficiary is specified, the Counterparty Correspondent field will be used to indicate the bank of the beneficiary. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these details have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us, (i.e. there is no customer record) the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPARTY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ in HK (the Cparty correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the Cparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the Intermed Add field. Validation Rules: 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is not allowed when a beneficiary number has been entered. Input is only allowed when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input is restricted to four lines of 35 characters.

        Parameters:
        param - the SecBenAdd to append
        Returns:
        nothing

      • addSecBk2bkIn

        public void addSecBk2bkIn(java.lang.CharSequence param)
        Appends the specified SecBk2bkIn to the end of the collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Provides instructions or additional information from the sending bank for the receiver, intermediary account with institution or beneficiary institution. Any details input by the user will be relayed to the receiver. Whenever this field is used in a message transmitted between countries with different languages, it is recommended that English is used. This field corresponds to field 72 on SWIFT messages, and must never be used for information for which another field is intended, or for instructions not required in a message. Validation Rules: Up to 35 characters (uppercase alpha or numeric) - Type S. Multivalue field. A maximum of 6 lines of 35 characters each will be allowed. If this field is used, the first multivalue must contain a code word followed by further information. All code words must be present on the SWIFT.CODE.WORDS files, and must be enclosed between slashes '/' at the beginning of the line. Further code words and information can be entered in subsequent multivalues, but additional information continued on a new line must be preceded by double slashes '//'.

        Parameters:
        param - the SecBk2bkIn to append
        Returns:
        nothing

        Field description: Contains the account number of the secondary counterparty or nominated beneficiary at their correspondent bank. The field will be used to provide the correspondent with the necessary details to credit the counterparty's or beneficiary's account. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several installments. If the bank is known to us (i.e. a customer record exists), details should be entered in the CPARTY.CORR.NO No field. If not, the should be entered in this multi-valued field. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us ===================== We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas ====================================== To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us (i.e. there is no customer record), the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally ===================================== Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty ==================================== The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input will only be accepted where Beneficiary or counterparty Correspondent details have been entered.

If the bank is known to us (i.e. a customer record exists), details should be entered in the counterparty Corr No field. If not, the should be entered in this multi-valued field. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us (i.e. there is no customer record), the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the CPARTY's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the CPARTY The CPARTY may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the CPARTY may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the CPARTY or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ' in HK (the CPARTY correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the CPARTY or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the INTERMED.ADD field. Validation Rules: Up to 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input in this field is not allowed when details have been entered in the intermediary bank number field. Input is only allowed when Our Account Pay represents a Nostro account. Input is not acceptable for Negotiated or other internal deals. Input is not allowed unless the CPARTY is known (i.e. deal sub-type is not 'BR'). Input will only be allowed if details of the correspondent have been entered. Input will not be allowed if there is a common correspondent signified by COMMONCORR being entered in the CPARTY.CORR.NO field.

        Parameters:
        param - the SecIntrAdd to append
        Returns:
        nothing

        public void clearSecBenAdd()

        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: This field is used when the secondary counterparty (This is normally the broker)of the deal instructs us to pay funds to another party who does not have an account with us. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several instalments. If the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the beneficiary details should be entered in the BENEFICIARY.NO field. If unknown to us, details should be entered in this multi-value field. Note that, where the beneficiary requests the funds into an account he has with us, this should be specified in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. It is important to note that when the Beneficiary is specified, the Counterparty Correspondent field will be used to indicate the bank of the beneficiary. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Validation Rules: 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is not allowed when a beneficiary number has been entered. Input is only allowed when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input is restricted to four lines of 35 characters.

        Field description: Provides instructions or additional information from the sending bank for the receiver, intermediary account with institution or beneficiary institution. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank ================================ Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank XYZ in HK (the counterparty correspondent), account Bank ABC (the counterparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the INTERMED.ADD field. Validation Rules: 34 character account number. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is only allowed when Our Account Pay is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input will only be accepted where Beneficiary or counterparty Correspondent details have been entered.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        nothing

      • clearSecIntrAdd

        public void clearSecIntrAdd()
        Clear the collection of SecIntrAdd
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Identifies any intermediary bank involved in the transaction and will be specified by the counterparty. If the intermediary is known to us (i.e. their is an associated customer record), the customer number of the intermediary bank should be entered in the INTERMED.BK.NO field. If not, details should be entered in this field. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several installments. If the bank is known to us (i.e. a customer record exists), details should be entered in the counterparty Corr No field. If not, the should be entered in this multi-valued field. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us (i.e. there is no customer record), the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the CPARTY's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the CPARTY The CPARTY may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the CPARTY may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the CPARTY or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ' in HK (the CPARTY correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the CPARTY or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the INTERMED.ADD field. Validation Rules: Up to 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input in this field is not allowed when details have been entered in the intermediary bank number field. Input is only allowed when Our Account Pay represents a Nostro account. Input is not acceptable for Negotiated or other internal deals. Input is not allowed unless the CPARTY is known (i.e. deal sub-type is not 'BR'). Input will only be allowed if details of the correspondent have been entered. Input will not be allowed if there is a common correspondent signified by COMMONCORR being entered in the CPARTY.CORR.NO field.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        nothing

      • getActionType

        public TField getActionType()
        Returns the ActionType

        Field description: Part of Regulatory Reporting information to a Trade Repository. Under the Regulatory Reporting to a Trade Repository, it is not only the initial trade that is reported but also the life cycle events of the Trade that follow. A change in the action type is indicative of an event on the contract and requires to be reported. Change in Action Types is allowed both manually and automatically. Specifies the ACTION.TYPE that is populated based on the event on trade. Input to this field is allowed only when OC module is installed. Validation Rules: Allowed optional values are N, M, E, C, Z and O N denotes that the ACTION.TYPE is NEW. Value of 'N' is defaulted for a new contract. User is also allowed to change the status to N if the previous status is E. E denotes that the ACTION.TYPE is REVERSE or Correction. In case of wrongly entered UTI values or a Temporary UTI was used previously, the old UTI should be reported with ACTION.TYPE as 'E' for error reporting first and then change the Action Type to NEW after keying in the actual UTI. This way the previous reporting with temporary UTI is replaced by the one with final UTI. Action Type E is also used to undo the reporting of a particular transaction done which should not have been done reported at all in the first instance. M denotes that the ACTION.TYPE is MODIFIED.When strike price and lots gets changed or in case of partial settlements,action type 'M' will get updated. C denotes the early termination of contract. If full settlement happens before maturity date(declaration date in case of OPTION contract),then action type will be updated as'C'. Z denotes Compression update. This means the trade being reported is generated out of a compression activity. O denotes OTHER types.Action type 'O' will be updated for assignment and exercise operations irrespective of partial or full settlement.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        TField - The ActionType

      • getCurrencyMarket

        public TField getCurrencyMarket()
        Returns the CurrencyMarket

        Field description: The system recognizes the need for a number of different markets within one currency. For this reason this field identifies which Exchange Rate Currency Market is accessed for this transaction. The system caters for the need to have more than one market within a given currency. The use of this field will only be applicable for those countries where the exchange market defines different rates for the same foreign Currency according to rules determined by the local authorities or local central bank. A typical example would be Belgium where foreign currencies are quoted on the Regular Market and also on the Free Market. Different sets of exchange rates will exist for these two markets. If default movement is not specified as 'DX', then if DEAL movement type has been specified on MU.TXN.GRP.CCY.MKT the market specified will be defaulted ito this field and the field will be made no input. If neither 'DX' is set or DEAL movement is specified, then input is mandatory in this field and may not be changed after authorisation. It is possible to specify separate markets to be used for COMM.CHRG and BROKERAGE. Any commission or change entries generated will use the specified market for COMM.CHRG if set up and similary BROKERAGE entries will use the BROKERAGE market if set up. If not set up the DEFAULT MOVEMENT currency market will be taken. The system allows the user to view the Foreign Exchange position by currency market when more than one market is applicable. Validation Rules: 1 numeric The market entered must appear on the Currency Market table. This field cannot be changed after authorisation. The market must exist on the local CURRENCY record. The market must exist on the CURRENCY record for both BUY and SELLCCY.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        TField - The CurrencyMarket

      • getOcClgStatus

        public TField getOcClgStatus()
        Returns the OcClgStatus

        Field description: Part of Regulatory Reporting information to a Trade Repository. Denotes the OC Clearing Status. Input to this field is allowed only when OC module is installed. Validation Rules: Allowed optional values are Bilateral, Submitted, Accepted, Rejected, Cleared and Terminated. BILATERAL - when a fresh contract is inputted this field should be updated as BILATERAL. The previous status should be null. SUBMITTED - when the inputted contract is submitted to Trade Repository it should get updated as SUBMITTED.The previous clearing status of the contract should be BILATERAL. ACCEPTED - when the contract is accepted by the Trade Repository it should get updated as ACCEPTED.The previous status should be SUBMITTED REJECTED - when the contract is rejected by the Trade Repository it should get updated as REJECTED.The previous status should be SUBMITTED CLEARED - When the status of the contract is ACCEPTED, User is expected to reverse the contract and enter a new one with Trade status as CLEARED.When the status is CLEARED, fields like CLG.MEM.ID, BILATERAL.REF are mandatory. Terminated - A cleared contract when cancelled/terminated by the Trade Repository should be updated as TERMINATED.The previous status should be CLEARED. This is a no change field.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        TField - The OcClgStatus

      • getSecBenAdd

        public List<TField> getSecBenAdd()
        Returns the collection of SecBenAdd

        Field description: This field is used when the secondary counterparty (This is normally the broker)of the deal instructs us to pay funds to another party who does not have an account with us. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several instalments. If the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the beneficiary details should be entered in the BENEFICIARY.NO field. If unknown to us, details should be entered in this multi-value field. Note that, where the beneficiary requests the funds into an account he has with us, this should be specified in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. It is important to note that when the Beneficiary is specified, the Counterparty Correspondent field will be used to indicate the bank of the beneficiary. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these details have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us, (i.e. there is no customer record) the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPARTY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ in HK (the Cparty correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the Cparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the Intermed Add field. Validation Rules: 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is not allowed when a beneficiary number has been entered. Input is only allowed when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input is restricted to four lines of 35 characters.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        List<TField> -

      • getSecBenAdd

        public TField getSecBenAdd(int idx)
        Returns the SecBenAdd at the specified position in this collection.

        Field description: This field is used when the secondary counterparty (This is normally the broker)of the deal instructs us to pay funds to another party who does not have an account with us. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several instalments. If the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the beneficiary details should be entered in the BENEFICIARY.NO field. If unknown to us, details should be entered in this multi-value field. Note that, where the beneficiary requests the funds into an account he has with us, this should be specified in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. It is important to note that when the Beneficiary is specified, the Counterparty Correspondent field will be used to indicate the bank of the beneficiary. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these details have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us, (i.e. there is no customer record) the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPARTY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the Intermed Add field. Validation Rules: 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is not allowed when a beneficiary number has been entered. Input is only allowed when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input is restricted to four lines of 35 characters.

      • getSecBk2bkIn

        public TField getSecBk2bkIn(int idx)
        Returns the SecBk2bkIn at the specified position in this collection.

        Field description: Provides instructions or additional information from the sending bank for the receiver, intermediary account with institution or beneficiary institution. Any details input by the user will be relayed to the receiver. Whenever this field is used in a message transmitted between countries with different languages, it is recommended that English is used. This field corresponds to field 72 on SWIFT messages, and must never be used for information for which another field is intended, or for instructions not required in a message. Validation Rules: Up to 35 characters (uppercase alpha or numeric) - Type S. Multivalue field. A maximum of 6 lines of 35 characters each will be allowed. If this field is used, the first multivalue must contain a code word followed by further information. All code words must be present on the SWIFT.CODE.WORDS files, and must be enclosed between slashes '/' at the beginning of the line. Further code words and information can be entered in subsequent multivalues, but additional information continued on a new line must be preceded by double slashes '//'.

        Parameters:
        idx - idx of the element to return
        Returns:
        TField -

        Field description: Contains the account number of the secondary counterparty or nominated beneficiary at their correspondent bank. If the bank is known to us (i.e. a customer record exists), the customer number of the bank will be entered in this field. If not, the details should be entered in the CPY.CORR.ADD field. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us, (i.e. there is no customer record) the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank ABC in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ' in (the counterparty correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the counterparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the INTERMED.ADD field. Validation Rules: 1-6 Numeric character Customer Number or 3-10 character customer mnemonic (uppercase alphanumeric or '.') - Type MNE Input in this field is optional. Default = as per Agency file when Our Account Pay = Nostro. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input must represent a valid customer on the Customer file. Input in this field is not allowed when details have been entered in the correspondent address field. Input is only allowed when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY represents a Nostro account. Input in this field or the next one (CPY.CORR.ADD) is mandatory when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY represents a Nostro account and no autorouting details (settlement instructions) exist on the Agency file for the counterparty of the deal. Input is not acceptable for Negotiated or other internal deals. Input is not allowed unless the counterparty is known (i.e. deal sub-type is not 'BR').

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        TField - The SecCpyNo

        Field description: When entitlements are pending the PENDING.DIARY field on DX.TRADE is marked with the Diary event. The trade cannot be amended whilst this is set.       • getSecIntrAdd

        public List<TField> getSecIntrAdd()
        Returns the collection of SecIntrAdd

        Field description: Identifies any intermediary bank involved in the transaction and will be specified by the counterparty. If the intermediary is known to us (i.e. their is an associated customer record), the customer number of the intermediary bank should be entered in the INTERMED.BK.NO field. If not, details should be entered in this field. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several installments. If the bank is known to us (i.e. a customer record exists), details should be entered in the counterparty Corr No field. If not, the should be entered in this multi-valued field. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us (i.e. there is no customer record), the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the CPARTY's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the CPARTY The CPARTY may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the CPARTY may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the CPARTY or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ' in HK (the CPARTY correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the CPARTY or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the INTERMED.ADD field. Validation Rules: Up to 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input in this field is not allowed when details have been entered in the intermediary bank number field. Input is only allowed when Our Account Pay represents a Nostro account. Input is not acceptable for Negotiated or other internal deals. Input is not allowed unless the CPARTY is known (i.e. deal sub-type is not 'BR'). Input will only be allowed if details of the correspondent have been entered. Input will not be allowed if there is a common correspondent signified by COMMONCORR being entered in the CPARTY.CORR.NO field.

      • getSecLimitRef

        public TField getSecLimitRef()
        Returns the SecLimitRef

        Field description: The limit reference identifying which Customer credit line to update. If no input is made in this field the Limits system will provide a default according to the LIMIT.REFERENCE record which has its field Application identifier set to DX.TRADE-SEC. The suffix -SEC is used by DX.TRADE to distinguish when a customer exists on the secondary side of the trade. If no match is found in the selective reference(s) the default will be the reference which is set to blank. The amount used to update limits is controlled by the selection field ,LIM.AMT.VAL.CONT, on DX.PARAMETER. Validation Rules: Optional Input. 3 to 7 numeric characters limit reference code. Input in this field must be a valid limit reference number.

        Returns:
        TField - The SecLimitRef

For FX OTC options , user is allowed to input any one of the SEC.PRICE or SEC.PREM.PRICE or SEC.TOTAL.PREM.AMT , the other two fields will be calculated by the sytem.

        Field description: The following field allows the user to automatically route Order's/Trades and the resultant fills from the system to another. Once a trade/order has been authorised the system can replicate the necessary trade/order data into the company specified in the DX.ACC.MASTER. the Secondary customer will be set as the RT.CUST.ID in the DX.ACC.MASTER. The T24 company in which the SEC.RT.CUST.ID (Secondary Routing Customer Id) is held, this will allow trades/orders to be mirrored into the T24 company Validation Rules: NO INPUT this data will be defaulted from the appropriate DX.ACC.MASTER record.

Validation Rules: Up to 6 alpha characters Auto populated field by information stored in DX.CONTRACT.MASTER under the CONTRACT.ID. Will default to FUTURE/OPTION/STOCK No Change Field Mandatory Input

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        TField - The TradeType

      • getTransferType

        public TField getTransferType()
        Returns the TransferType

        Field description: Specifies the type of trade executed through a broker and the process route it takes to be cleared for the bank's account. Drop down field with the options TAKEON and RVPDVP, TAKEON- CONT, TRANSFER, TRANSFER.INC and TRANSFER.INC.PAY, TRANSFER.INC, TRANSFER.INC.PAY and EXECUTION, CLEARING, SWITCH and BOTH. TAKEON and RVPDVP: Used during data migration for take-on of Customer Trades. No entries and messages are posted and sent. TAKEON-CONT: Used for takeover of Own Book Trades. System generates only CRF entries and no messages are sent. TRANSFER: Gets updated in TRANSFER.TYPE for the trades generated from internal transfers. TRANSFER.INC and TRANSFER.INC.PAY: Moves the trade/position from one portfolio to another. The field DEST.CUST.PORT becomes mandatory. TRANSFER.INC: Used for informative / reporting purpose only. System does not generate any entries or messages. TRANSFER.INC.PAY: Generates entries and advices when the fields FEE and ADVICE are set to YES. EXECUTION, CLEARING, SWITCH and BOTH: Used for informative / reporting purpose. Behaves as normal trade.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        TField - The TransferType

      • getTreasuryCustomer

        public TField getTreasuryCustomer()

        Field description: TREASURY.CUSTOMER: Identifies if the counter party is a treasury customer or not When the user indicates that the counter party is not a treasury customer then he is allowed to enter the SEC.PRICE manually along with the PRI.PRICE. Difference between the primary and secondary internal prices will be posted to the profit and loss category code mentioned in the DX.EVENT.TYPE record BP. Validation Rules: Valid inputs are NULL and NO If this field is NULL then user is not allowed to amend the SEC.PRICE which is If this field is NO then the user can amend the SEC.PRICE

      • getUniTranId

        public TField getUniTranId()
        Returns the UniTranId

        Field description: Part of Regulatory Reporting information to a Trade Repository All Trades should have a Unique Transaction Identifier (UTI) which is generated, communicated and matched. Determination of who generates the UTI should follow the existing industry best practices for that Asset class. The UTI.USI.API attached in OC.PARAMETER and invoked during DX.TRADE input determines who is the party responsible for UTI generation and does the following. If a value is present during deal capture the API is not invoked, on the assumption that the UTI is generated and supplied by the other Counterparty. If no value is present during the deal capture, the API is invoked to determine the party responsible for generating the UTI. If the Other counterparty is responsible, still an UTI is generated with a suffix as TEMP to show that the UTI from the other counterparty is awaited and in the meantime, the reporting is done with a Temporary ID. If T24 Bank is responsible for UTI generation, then the same is generated without TEMP. Where a reporting has been made with UTI having TEMP as suffix and subsequently the Counterparty supplies the UTI, the following procedure has to be followed to ensure reporting with actual UTI. The field Action Type needs to be changed to E and record to be authorized. Later, the UTI field should be modified with the actual UTI received. Set the Action Type field to N and authorize the record. In this way, the previous reporting gets cancelled and the new reporting goes with correct UTI. For FX OTC trades, the UTI will be defaulted by considering Customer and Bank as the DEALCPARTY and BANKCPARTY. For ETD trades between customer and broker where bank act as Implied Principal,the UTI would be supplied by broker. Input to this field is allowed only when OC module is installed. Validation Rules : Can contain up to 52 alphanumeric characters.

        Parameters:
        Returns:
        TField - The UniTranId

      • insertSecBenAdd

        public void insertSecBenAdd(TField param, int pos)
        Insert the specified SecBenAdd to the specified position in the collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: This field is used when the secondary counterparty (This is normally the broker)of the deal instructs us to pay funds to another party who does not have an account with us. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several instalments. If the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the beneficiary details should be entered in the BENEFICIARY.NO field. If unknown to us, details should be entered in this multi-value field. Note that, where the beneficiary requests the funds into an account he has with us, this should be specified in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. It is important to note that when the Beneficiary is specified, the Counterparty Correspondent field will be used to indicate the bank of the beneficiary. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these details have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us, (i.e. there is no customer record) the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPARTY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ in HK (the Cparty correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the Cparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the Intermed Add field. Validation Rules: 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is not allowed when a beneficiary number has been entered. Input is only allowed when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input is restricted to four lines of 35 characters.

        Parameters:
        param - the SecBenAdd to append
        pos - The position where to insert the value.
        Returns:
        nothing

      • insertSecBk2bkIn

        public void insertSecBk2bkIn(TField param, int pos)
        Insert the specified SecBk2bkIn to the specified position in the collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Provides instructions or additional information from the sending bank for the receiver, intermediary account with institution or beneficiary institution. Any details input by the user will be relayed to the receiver. Whenever this field is used in a message transmitted between countries with different languages, it is recommended that English is used. This field corresponds to field 72 on SWIFT messages, and must never be used for information for which another field is intended, or for instructions not required in a message. Validation Rules: Up to 35 characters (uppercase alpha or numeric) - Type S. Multivalue field. A maximum of 6 lines of 35 characters each will be allowed. If this field is used, the first multivalue must contain a code word followed by further information. All code words must be present on the SWIFT.CODE.WORDS files, and must be enclosed between slashes '/' at the beginning of the line. Further code words and information can be entered in subsequent multivalues, but additional information continued on a new line must be preceded by double slashes '//'.

        Parameters:
        param - the SecBk2bkIn to append
        pos - The position where to insert the value.
        Returns:
        nothing

      • insertSecBk2bkIn

        public void insertSecBk2bkIn(java.lang.CharSequence param, int pos)

        Field description: Provides instructions or additional information from the sending bank for the receiver, intermediary account with institution or beneficiary institution. Any details input by the user will be relayed to the receiver. Whenever this field is used in a message transmitted between countries with different languages, it is recommended that English is used. This field corresponds to field 72 on SWIFT messages, and must never be used for information for which another field is intended, or for instructions not required in a message. Validation Rules: Up to 35 characters (uppercase alpha or numeric) - Type S. Multivalue field. A maximum of 6 lines of 35 characters each will be allowed. If this field is used, the first multivalue must contain a code word followed by further information. All code words must be present on the SWIFT.CODE.WORDS files, and must be enclosed between slashes '/' at the beginning of the line. Further code words and information can be entered in subsequent multivalues, but additional information continued on a new line must be preceded by double slashes '//'.

        Parameters:
        param - the SecBk2bkIn to append
        pos - The position where to insert the value.
        Returns:
        nothing

      • insertSecCpyAdd

        public void insertSecCpyAdd(TField param, int pos)
        Insert the specified SecCpyAdd to the specified position in the collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Contains the account number of the secondary counterparty or nominated beneficiary at their correspondent bank. The field will be used to provide the correspondent with the necessary details to credit the counterparty's or beneficiary's account. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several installments. If the bank is known to us (i.e. a customer record exists), details should be entered in the CPARTY.CORR.NO No field. If not, the should be entered in this multi-valued field. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us ===================== We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas ====================================== To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us (i.e. there is no customer record), the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally ===================================== Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty ==================================== The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank ================================ Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank XYZ in HK (the counterparty correspondent), account Bank ABC (the counterparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the INTERMED.ADD field. Validation Rules: 34 character account number. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is only allowed when Our Account Pay is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input will only be accepted where Beneficiary or counterparty Correspondent details have been entered.

        Parameters:
        param - the SecCpyAdd to append
        pos - The position where to insert the value.
        Returns:
        nothing

It will also be part of the Bank to Bank information printed on the confirmation sent to the CPARTY except if overridden by another narrative. Validation Rules: Up to 6 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is limited to 6 lines of 35 characters.

        Parameters:

      • removeSecBenAdd

        public void removeSecBenAdd(int idx)
        Remove the SecBenAdd at the specified position in this collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: This field is used when the secondary counterparty (This is normally the broker)of the deal instructs us to pay funds to another party who does not have an account with us. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The counterparty will advise us of where the money which we have sold is to be paid and we will advise them where we require the currency purchased to be remitted. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several instalments. If the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the beneficiary details should be entered in the BENEFICIARY.NO field. If unknown to us, details should be entered in this multi-value field. Note that, where the beneficiary requests the funds into an account he has with us, this should be specified in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. It is important to note that when the Beneficiary is specified, the Counterparty Correspondent field will be used to indicate the bank of the beneficiary. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these details have not yet been defined on the Agency file. If the bank is not known to us, (i.e. there is no customer record) the bank's name and address should be entered in the multi-valued field CPARTY.CORR.ADD. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ' in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank 'XYZ in HK (the Cparty correspondent), account Bank 'ABC' (the Cparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the Intermed Add field. Validation Rules: 4 lines of 35 characters. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is not allowed when a beneficiary number has been entered. Input is only allowed when OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input is restricted to four lines of 35 characters.

        Parameters:
        idx - index of the element to remove
        Returns:
        nothing

      • removeSecBk2bkIn

        public void removeSecBk2bkIn(int idx)
        Remove the SecBk2bkIn at the specified position in this collection.
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Provides instructions or additional information from the sending bank for the receiver, intermediary account with institution or beneficiary institution. Any details input by the user will be relayed to the receiver. Whenever this field is used in a message transmitted between countries with different languages, it is recommended that English is used. This field corresponds to field 72 on SWIFT messages, and must never be used for information for which another field is intended, or for instructions not required in a message. Validation Rules: Up to 35 characters (uppercase alpha or numeric) - Type S. Multivalue field. A maximum of 6 lines of 35 characters each will be allowed. If this field is used, the first multivalue must contain a code word followed by further information. All code words must be present on the SWIFT.CODE.WORDS files, and must be enclosed between slashes '/' at the beginning of the line. Further code words and information can be entered in subsequent multivalues, but additional information continued on a new line must be preceded by double slashes '//'.

        Parameters:
        idx - index of the element to remove
        Returns:
        nothing

        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Contains the account number of the secondary counterparty or nominated beneficiary at their correspondent bank. When a contract matures, funds must be moved to actually settle the contract. This involves paying the counterparty or his nominated beneficiary for the currency sold and receiving funds for the currency purchased. The delivery of funds will normally be as one payment but may be in several installments. The counterparty may ask us to pay the amount sold in a number of ways: To an account with us ===================== We may pay the funds directly into an account provided it is in the same currency as that being sold. To make payment directly to a counterparty's internal account the relevant account number should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field and no other input will be necessary in this field. To an account at another bank overseas ====================================== To pay money to another bank overseas we would have to advise our agent, in the country concerned, to pay to the counterparty's bank. In this case, the Nostro account number of our agent should be entered in the OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY field. If the counterparty's bank is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), then the bank's number should be entered in CPARTY.CORR.NO if these have not yet been defined on the Agency file. When known, the counterparty's account number at his bank should be entered in the field CPARTY.BANK.ACC. To an account at another bank locally ===================================== Where payment is to be effected locally, settlement can be through a number of different methods. The most common are Banker's Payments, CHIPS, or CHAPS. In all cases, the number of our internal clearing account, or our clearing agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Details of the counterparty's bank account should be completed as detailed above. To a beneficiary of the counterparty ==================================== The counterparty may nominate a third party beneficiary of the funds. If the beneficiary is to be paid by crediting an account with us, the account number should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. If the beneficiary does not have an account with us, the internal clearing number or Nostro account of our agent should be entered in OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY. Where we are paying to another bank but the beneficiary is known to us (i.e. there is a customer record), the customer number of the beneficiary will be entered in the field BENEFICIARY.NO. Where no relationship exists, the payment details will be entered in the multi-valued field BENFCY.ADD. Payment via an intermediary bank ================================ Occasionally the counterparty may ask for payment to be made through an intermediary bank. This occurs where the counterparty or beneficiary's correspondent is not in the country of the currency involved. As an example, let us say that the Bank 'ABC' in Hong Kong uses Bank 'XYZ in Hong Kong as their dollar agent. When a dollar payment is to be made we would pay American Bank in New York (the Intermediary) for Bank XYZ in HK (the counterparty correspondent), account Bank ABC (the counterparty or Beneficiary). The Intermediary can be entered as a number in the INTERMED.BK.NO field if a customer relationship exists (i.e. there is a customer number) or as narrative in the INTERMED.ADD field. Validation Rules: 34 character account number. Multivalue field associated with field range OUR.ACCOUNT.PAY to REC.ADV.NARR. Input is only allowed when Our Account Pay is a Nostro account. Input is not allowed for deal sub-types 'BR','IN', and 'NE'. Input will only be accepted where Beneficiary or counterparty Correspondent details have been entered.

      • setActionType

        public void setActionType(TField value)
        Set the specified value for ActionType
        Throws an UnsupportedOperationException if the object is not modifiable.

        Field description: Part of Regulatory Reporting information to a Trade Repository. Under the Regulatory Reporting to a Trade Repository, it is not only the initial trade that is reported but also the life cycle events of the Trade that follow. A change in the action type is indicative of an event on the contract and requires to be reported. Change in Action Types is allowed both manually and automatically. Specifies the ACTION.TYPE that is populated based on the event on trade. Input to this field is allowed only when OC module is installed. Validation Rules: Allowed optional values are N, M, E, C, Z and O N denotes that the ACTION.TYPE is NEW. Value of 'N' is defaulted for a new contract. User is also allowed to change the status to N if the previous status is E. E denotes that the ACTION.TYPE is REVERSE or Correction. In case of wrongly entered UTI values or a Temporary UTI was used previously, the old UTI should be reported with ACTION.TYPE as 'E' for error reporting first and then change the Action Type to NEW after keying in the actual UTI. This way the previous reporting with temporary UTI is replaced by the one with final UTI. Action Type E is also used to undo the reporting of a particular transaction done which should not have been done reported at all in the first instance. M denotes that the ACTION.TYPE is MODIFIED.When strike price and lots gets changed or in case of partial settlements,action type 'M' will get updated. C denotes the early termination of contract. If full settlement happens before maturity date(declaration date in case of OPTION contract),then action type will be updated as'C'. Z denotes Compression update. This means the trade being reported is generated out of a compression activity. O denotes OTHER types.Action type 'O' will be updated for assignment and exercise operations irrespective of partial or full settlement.

        Parameters:
        value - The value to set
        Returns:
        nothing
